Beautiful, colonial style restaurant, located in the heart of the city.

This place has beautiful interior design, a lot of vintage collections, wonderful paintings, and most importantly, delicious food, and beverages.

You can try a lot of Indonesian cuisines and great coffee, particularly from Kawisari area.

we came here for lunch with a big group, and we really enjoyed the vibes. It was a busy Friday afternoon, but the service is good and fast. We had grilled chicken, deep-fried duck, Pecel and veggie sauteed, tongue stew, fried corn fritters, Tempe mendoan, and many more. They have various Indonesian famous snacks and beverages as well. They also provide wine, cocktails and also cigars! The coffee is sooo good, you have to try!

They have space upstairs and outside like balcony. The first floor is disability friendly, ♿️✅. It has toilet for wheelchair user as well. Second floor has stairs, though.

Parking is available although not too big.

text.text:
After visiting several outlets, I just realized that the Toko Kopi Tuku indoor area are not particularly spacious, including the newly opened outlet in Sabang.

It is located inside Hero & Guardian on the second floor. The staircase is quite photogenic, but be mindful of the steps when taking photos here. Try not to disturb other visitors. Upon entering, the area is really small. There are only a few seats near the entrance and a few benches. There is a place to put your drinks, but you can't sit and enjoy your drink. It's primarily focused on takeout purchases.

Here, they offer packaged milk coffee and snacks, in addition to the regular milk coffee (IDR 20K). Some are already prepared, just pick them up and pay at the cashier. I ordered a regular milk coffee and asked for less ice. It tasted better that way, and it felt creamy without being diluted by melting ice cubes.

Awful! Don’t Book! If you’re finding a good place stay in Jakarta, Do NOT book this hotel!!!

The hotel doesn’t look great like their photo provided. Their facilities are old, stained and broken. The sink had cracked and broken, toilet leaked, also their aircon is not functioning.

Please, if you do not want to ruin your holiday or a business trip. Avoid this one!!
Rather give a 0 star if I could.

3 Reasons WHY I recommend this cafe to you (in my versions) 🥰 :
1. They have seasonal Menu which change every month (creative!)
2. Their single origin coffee also change around weekly (I tastes 3 different single origins in three times visits in 6 months). For house blend stay the same
3. Sometimes, they sell unique snacks : like this time I find "Emping granola" which they made the packaged inspired by medicine box for gout 😂

Basically they sells local snacks and mini food like : nasi kucing (literally nasi kucing because the portions is petite, hehe), choi pan, tahu goreng, bakso goreng, etc

The cafe has limiting seating area inside and inviting intimacy when you eat some snacks while sipping your favorite coffee in the morning. (worry not, they have the outdoor area, if you want to vaping or smoking)

This one also, use some spice in their dessert as the component.

You always have a reason for comeback : Their seasonal menu 🫶🏼

Thank you and will came back soon ! 🤩🥳😍

Temu Cafe seems to be a great option for breakfast in the Thamrin area, offering a nice ambiance, ample space, and a menu with some standout dishes. The interior and spacious layout clearly make it an attractive spot, especially for a relaxing breakfast.

My experience was a mixed bag, with some hits and a minor miss. I started with an Americano, which I unfortunately didn't get specific details about the coffee but it served its purpose as a morning caffeine kick. More interesting was the Charcoal Milk. While the creamy texture was undeniably decadent, the sweetness unfortunately masked the earthy, slightly smoky character typically associated with charcoal. It felt more like a flavored milk than a true charcoal experience.However, the food truly impressed. The Club Sandwich was a classic done exceptionally well. Sometimes simplicity is key, and Temu Cafe seems to understand that. It sounds like the ingredients were high quality and perfectly proportioned, making it a delicious and satisfying pick.

The Caesar Salad also earned my approval. Fresh ingredients are paramount in a salad like this, and the mention of them being "fresh" is a great sign. The creamy dressing, especially when paired with a crunchy slice of bread, sounds like the perfect complement.

The Teh Tarik was also recommended. Really good.

Good service and friendly staff. Great affordable price with price average between Rp. 25k-45k.  Parking is a problem though as in for most restaurants on this street. Will definitely return to try more dishes.
